# Retirement Planning Guide — Client A
*Created: June 2026 | A practical guide for a couple approaching retirement at 62, built as an educational framework. All names and identifying details are anonymized. For precise calculations, consult a fiduciary or fee-only financial advisor.*

---

## Context and purpose

Client A is turning 62 and planning retirement. Her spouse is still working, earns a strong salary, and holds company shares. He plans to transition around age 65, either staying in his current role or moving to something less stressful. This guide covers the 5 main retirement risks, a 3-bucket withdrawal strategy, Social Security timing, Roth conversions, RMDs, and a 3-year cash reserve framework.

---

## The 5 risks retirees go broke in the first 5 years

### 1. Sequence of return risk
A major market drop in the first few years of retirement can permanently damage a portfolio even if markets recover. The order of returns matters as much as the average.

**Their edge:** The spouse is still working. They are not forced to sell in a downturn. The 3-year cash reserve handles living expenses while the portfolio heals. Even a lower-stress part-time role after 65 reduces portfolio pressure significantly.

### 2. Spending too much too soon
The retirement honeymoon effect. Travel, renovations, gifting — early overspending compounds quietly.

**The fix:** Set a clear monthly income target and review actual spending annually.

### 3. Not enough cash reserve
Without a liquidity buffer, retirees panic-sell at the worst moment.

**The plan:** 3-year reserve split between HYSA (6-12 months, liquid) and Treasury bills (remaining 2 years, state and local tax exempt).

### 4. Claiming Social Security too early
Every year of delay after full retirement age = approximately 8% more per year, guaranteed.

| Age | Benefit |
|-----|---------|
| 62 | ~58% of full benefit |
| 65 | ~73% |
| 67 | 100% (full retirement age) |
| 70 | ~124% — maximum |

There is no single right answer. The decision depends on health, income needs, and other income sources. Use the Social Security timing analyzer: https://ft-socialsecuritytiming.lovable.app/

### 5. Supporting adult children
Unplanned financial support to family is a common and underappreciated cause of retirement shortfalls. Any support should be a conscious, planned decision — not a default.

