## The 3-year cash reserve

**Example at $12,000/month income target:**

| Timeframe | Amount needed |
|-----------|--------------|
| Annual | $144,000 |
| 3-year reserve | $432,000 |

| Account | Purpose | Notes |
|---------|---------|-------|
| HYSA | 6-12 months liquid | 4-5% yield, fully accessible |
| Treasury bills (T-bills) | Remaining ~2 years | State and local tax exempt, rolling 3-6 month terms |

**Why 3 years works:** The average bear market lasts 9-18 months. Three years means never selling investments during a downturn. The portfolio recovers on its own timeline.

---

## The 5-step playbook

1. **Know your buckets** — Label every account: taxable, tax-deferred, or tax-free
2. **Follow the withdrawal order** — Taxable first, tax-deferred second, tax-free last
3. **Use gap years for Roth conversions** — Live off cash or taxable income while income is low. Pay conversion tax from outside the IRA
4. **Be intentional about Social Security timing** — Run the numbers, understand the tradeoffs, decide based on income needs and health. Revisit the decision together when the working spouse transitions
5. **Review every year and stay flexible** — Income, balances, tax bracket, spending. They spent decades building this — be just as intentional taking it out

